        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Dust Observations: 
We are requesting a total of 4.04 hours with overhead (seven pointing mosaic) of ALMA 12 m time at 230 GHz to map the dust continuum emission in a targeted region of the Eastern star forming HI cloud of the nearby, low metallicity galaxy Sextans A (see Figure 2).  The dust continuum emission is expected to be quite faint in Sextans A due to its low metallicity.  In order to compute the expected continuum flux from the dust grains at 230 GHz we use the equation

S_nu = tau_nu * Omega * B_nu(nu,T_d)

where S_nu is the flux density, tau_nu is the optical depth, Omega is the solid angle of the beam, B_nu is the Planck function, nu is the observed frequency, and T_d is the assumed dust temperature.  We use the relation

tau_nu = N_H * C_nu

where N_H is the column density of hydrogen atoms and C_nu is the cross-sectional area of the dust grains.  We assume the dust has a temperature of 30 K, N_H = 3x10^21 cm^-2, and C_nu = 3.25x10^-27 (Draine 2003).  C_nu was derived for a Milky Way gas-to-dust ratio.  We assume here that the lower metallicity of Sextans A will give way to a higher gas-to-dust ratio and we use a value of 10 (thus tau_nu = 10 * N_H * C_nu).  With these assumptions we compute a value for S_nu of 270 uJy for the 1.6'' beam of ALMA's Band 6 configuration.  Our proposed 4.04 hour observation will reach a sensitivity 20 uJy over our 6.56 GHz bandwidth.  Thus we will achieve a signal-to-noise of at least 10 in our dust continuum map.

CO Observations: 
The CO (J=2-1) emission line is within the bandwidth selected for our dust continuum observations.  If we assume that the molecular clouds in Sextans A are similar in size to those in the Milky Way (25-50 pc) then ALMA's 1.6'' beam (~10 pc) will resolve the individual clouds.  The typical resolved surface brightness of the CO clouds in the Milky Way is ~3.5 K.  However, given that previous attempts at detecting CO in low metallicity galaxies have been unsuccessful, the actual surface brightness may be lower.  Therefore we are requesting a deep exposure that will reach an rms sensitivity of 0.025 K in 0.635 km s^-1 velocity bins. These deep integrations will also help detect the dust continuum associated with both the HI gas and the more dense molecular clouds.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
